window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>1","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"WATER","question":"The processes involved in the treatment of water for town supply include. I. filtration. II. coagulation. III. chlorination  IV. distillation.","images":[],"options":{"A":"iv","B":"i and ii","C":"iii and iv","D":"i, ii and iii"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The treatment of water for town supply typically includes filtration, coagulation, and chlorination. Filtration removes suspended particles, coagulation helps in aggregating impurities for easier removal, and chlorination disinfects the water. Distillation is not commonly used for large-scale water treatment due to its high energy requirements.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>2","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"CHEMISTRY OF CARBON COMPOUNDS : PETROLEUM/CRUDE OIL","question":"Which of the following processes is/are used to improve the yield and quality of petrol? I. Cracking II. Catalytic reforming III. Use of additives IV. Fractional distillation.","images":[],"options":{"A":"iv","B":"i and ii","C":"iii and iv","D":"i, ii and iii"},"answer":"D","explanation":"To improve the yield and quality of petrol, processes such as cracking (breaking down larger hydrocarbons), catalytic reforming (rearranging molecular structures to improve quality), and the use of additives (to enhance performance) are employed. Fractional distillation is also used to separate different components of crude oil, making it relevant to petrol production.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>3","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"CHEMICAL BONDS : SHAPES OF MOLECULAR COMPOUNDS.","question":"Which of the following molecules is/are linear in shape? I. N2 II. CO2 III. NH3 IV. H2O","images":[],"options":{"A":"iv","B":"i and ii","C":"iii and iv","D":"i, ii and iii"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The molecules N2 and CO2 are linear in shape. N2 consists of two nitrogen atoms bonded together, while CO2 has a central carbon atom double bonded to two oxygen atoms, forming a straight line. NH3 (ammonia) and H2O (water) are not linear; NH3 has a trigonal pyramidal shape, and H2O has a bent shape.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>4","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE ATOM : PERIODICITY OF THE ELEMENTS","question":"If an atom of an element X is represented as 424 which of the following deductions is/are correct? I. X is chemically inactive II. An atom of X has two neutrons  III. An atom of X has only one shell IV belongs to period one of the Periodic Table","images":[],"options":{"A":"iv","B":"i and ii","C":"iii and iv","D":"i, ii, iii and iv"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The symbol  424     X means atomic number = 2 (so X is helium) and mass number = 4.    I: Chemically inactive \u2014 helium is a noble gas, so true.    II: Neutrons = mass \u2212 protons = 4 \u2212 2 = 2, so true.    III: Only one shell \u2014 both electrons occupy the first (only) shell, so true.    IV: Belongs to period 1 \u2014 elements with electrons only in the first shell are in period 1, so true.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>5","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"METALS AND THEIR COMPOUNDS : REACTIVITY OF IRON AND ALUMINIUM WITH AIR, WATER AND ACIDS","question":"Which of the following can displace copper from non aqueous solution of copper(II) salt? I. Mg II. AI III. Zn IV. Fe","images":[],"options":{"A":"iv","B":"i and ii","C":"iii and iv","D":"i, ii, iii and iv"},"answer":"D","explanation":"A metal can displace another from its compound if it is more reactive (higher in the reactivity series).    Copper (Cu) is below Mg, Al, Zn, and Fe in the reactivity series.    Therefore, all four metals (Mg, Al, Zn, Fe) can displace copper from its non-aqueous salt solution.     So the correct option is I, II, III, and IV.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>6","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"ISOMERISM","question":"Cis-butenedioic acid and trans-butenedioic acid have the same I. physical properties. II. spatial arrangement III. relative molar mass. IV. functional groups.","images":[],"options":{"A":"iv","B":"i and ii","C":"iii and iv","D":"i, ii and iii"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Geometric isomers (cis/trans) have the same molecular formula, hence the same relative molar mass (III).    They also contain the same functional groups (IV), here \u2013COOH groups.    But they differ in spatial arrangement (II) (cis = same side, trans = opposite sides).    Because of this difference in arrangement, they also differ in physical properties (I) such as melting and boiling points, solubility, etc.    Thus, the correct deductions are III and IV only.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>7","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"METALS AND THEIR COMPOUNDS : PROPERTIES AND USES OF ALUMINIUM AND ITS COMPOUNDS","question":"The properties of aluminium which make the metal useful in the manufacture of cooking utensils includes its I. resistance to corrosion. II. lightness and durability. III. ability to conduct heat and electricity IV. ability to react both acids and bases.","images":[],"options":{"A":"iv","B":"i and ii","C":"iii and iv","D":"i, ii and iii"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Aluminium is useful in cooking utensils due to its resistance to corrosion (I), lightness and durability (II), and ability to conduct heat and electricity (III). However, its ability to react with both acids and bases (IV) is not a property that contributes to its usefulness in cooking utensils. Therefore, the correct answer is 'i, ii and iii'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>8","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"REDOX REACTIONS : ELECTROLYSIS","question":"In which of the following is electrolysis not applicable? I. Production of sulphur (IV) oxide II. Extraction of iron III. Extraction of aluminium IV. Purification of copper.","images":[],"options":{"A":"iv","B":"i and ii","C":"iii and iv","D":"i, ii and iii"},"answer":"B","explanation":"I. Production of SO\u2082 \u2192 done by burning sulphur in oxygen, not electrolysis.    II. Extraction of iron \u2192 carried out in a blast furnace by reduction with carbon, not electrolysis.    III. Extraction of aluminium \u2192 requires electrolysis of alumina (Hall\u2013H\u00e9roult process).    IV. Purification of copper \u2192 done by electrolysis.    So electrolysis is not applicable in I and II only.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>9","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"METALS AND THEIR COMPOUNDS : ALLOYS","question":"Tin is one of the constituents of I. bronze. II. soft solder.III. duralumin. IV. brass","images":[],"options":{"A":"iv","B":"i and ii","C":"iii and iv","D":"i, ii and iii"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Tin is a constituent of bronze (I) and soft solder (II), but it is not a component of duralumin (III) or brass (IV). Duralumin is an alloy primarily of aluminium, while brass is an alloy of copper and zinc. Therefore, the correct answer is 'i and ii'. Bronze = Copper + Tin.    Soft solder = Lead + Tin.    Duralumin = Aluminium + Copper + Manganese + Magnesium (no tin).    Brass = Copper + Zinc (no tin).    Therefore, tin is present only in bronze and soft solder.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>10","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"ACIDS, BASES AND SALTS : SALTS","question":"The general methods of preparing salts include I. neutralization. II. precipitation. III. double decomposition IV. action of an acid on a metal.","images":[],"options":{"A":"iv","B":"i and ii","C":"iii and iv","D":"i, ii, iii and iv"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The general methods of preparing salts include neutralization (I), precipitation (II), double decomposition (III), and action of an acid on a metal (IV). All these methods are valid for salt preparation. Therefore, the correct answer is 'i, ii, iii and iv'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>11","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"STANDARD SEPARATION TECHNIQUES FOR MIXTURES : SEPARATION TECHNIQUES","question":"The components of universal indicator solution can best be separated by","images":[],"options":{"A":"chromatography","B":"filtration","C":"evaporation","D":"crystallization"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The components of a universal indicator solution can best be separated by chromatography. Chromatography is a technique used to separate mixtures into their individual components based on their different affinities to a stationary phase and a mobile phase. In the case of a universal indicator, which is a mixture of various pH-sensitive dyes, chromatography allows for the separation of these dyes effectively.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>12","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"ACIDS, BASES AND SALTS : ACIDS","question":"The number of replaceable hydrogen atoms in one acid indicates its","images":[],"options":{"A":"basicity","B":"acidity","C":"alkalinity","D":"reactivity"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The basicity of an acid is the number of replaceable hydrogen atoms (ionizable H\u207a ions) present in one molecule of the acid.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>13","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"CHEMISTRY OF CARBON COMPOUNDS : ALKENES","question":"Catalytic hydrogenation of alkenes produces compounds with the general formula","images":[],"options":{"A":"CnH2n+1OH","B":"CnH2n+1","C":"CnH2n+2","D":"CnH2n-2"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Catalytic hydrogenation of alkenes produces compounds with the general formula CnH2n+2. This process involves the addition of hydrogen (H2) across the double bond of alkenes, converting them into alkanes, which have the formula CnH2n+2. This reflects the saturation of the carbon chain.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>14","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"CHEMICAL KINETICS AND EQUILIBRIUM SYSTEM : EQUILIBRIUM","question":"A measure of the degree of disorder in a chemical system is known as the","images":[],"options":{"A":"enthalpy","B":"free energy","C":"activation energy","D":"entrophy"},"answer":"D","explanation":"A measure of the degree of disorder in a chemical system is known as entropy. Entropy is a thermodynamic quantity that represents the amount of disorder or randomness in a system. Higher entropy indicates a greater degree of disorder, while lower entropy indicates a more ordered state.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>15","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"STOICHIOMETRY AND CHEMICAL REACTIONS : LAWS OF CHEMICAL COMBINATION.","question":"In any chemical reaction, the total mass of the products is always equal to that of the reactants. This is statement of the law of","images":[],"options":{"A":"definite proportion","B":"conservation of matter","C":"multiple proportions","D":"reciprocal proportions"},"answer":"B","explanation":"In any chemical reaction, the total mass of the products is always equal to that of the reactants. This is a statement of the law of conservation of matter, which states that matter cannot be created or destroyed in an isolated system. Therefore, the mass remains constant throughout the reaction.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>16","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"METALS AND THEIR COMPOUNDS : PROPERTIES AND USES OF SODIUM AND ITS COMPOUNDS.","question":"Which of the following is not a property of magnesium oxide?","images":[],"options":{"A":"High melting point","B":"Dissolution in polar solvents","C":"Presence of ionic bonds","D":"Low binding energy"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Magnesium oxide (MgO) is a strongly bonded ionic compound formed by Mg\u00b2\u207a and O\u00b2\u207b ions. Its properties include:    High melting point (A): due to strong electrostatic attraction between oppositely charged ions.    Ionic bonds (C): MgO is held together by ionic bonding.    Crystal lattice (D): ions are arranged in a giant ionic lattice.    Interaction with polar solvents (B): though only sparingly soluble, it can react with water to form alkaline Mg(OH)\u2082.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>17","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"ENERGY AND ENERGY CHANGES : ENERGY AND ENTHALPY","question":"23592U + 10n + 14556Ba + 8736Kr + 10n + energy. The reaction represented by the equation above is","images":[],"options":{"A":"an alpha particle emission","B":"an endothermic reaction","C":"a thermal ionization","D":"nuclear fission"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The reaction represented is a nuclear fission reaction. In this process, a heavy nucleus (Uranium-235) absorbs a neutron and splits into two smaller nuclei (Barium-145 and Krypton-87), along with the release of additional neutrons and energy. This is characteristic of fission, where the nucleus breaks apart, as opposed to fusion, where smaller nuclei combine.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>18","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"CHEMICAL KINETICS AND EQUILIBRIUM SYSTEM : RATE OF REACTIONS","question":"Which of the following would increase the rate of reaction of chips of a metal M as shown in the equation below?   M(s) + 2HCI(aq) \u2192 MCI2(aq) + H2(g)","images":[],"options":{"A":"Diluting the hydrochloric acid","B":"Adding some distilled water","C":"Decreasing the temperature","D":"Grinding the metal into powder"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Grinding the metal into powder increases the surface area of the metal, which allows for more collisions between the metal and hydrochloric acid, thus increasing the rate of reaction. This is a fundamental concept in reaction kinetics where surface area plays a crucial role.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>19","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"ACIDS, BASES AND SALTS : ACID-BASE REACTIONS","question":"The oxidation number of phosphorus in PO43- is","images":[],"options":{"A":"+1","B":"+2","C":"+3","D":"+5"},"answer":"D","explanation":"In the phosphate ion (PO43-), phosphorus has an oxidation state of +5. This can be determined by considering the overall charge of the ion and the typical oxidation states of oxygen, which is -2. Therefore, the oxidation state of phosphorus must be +5 to balance the charge.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>20","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"STOICHIOMETRY AND CHEMICAL REACTIONS : AMOUNT OF SUBSTANCE.","question":"The number of atoms in 1.2g of carbon - 12 isotope is","images":[],"options":{"A":"1.00 x 1022","B":"6.02 x 1022","C":"1.20 x 1023","D":"1.00 x 1023"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The number of atoms in 1.2g of carbon-12 can be calculated using Avogadro's number (6.02 x 10^23 atoms/mol). Since 1 mole of carbon-12 weighs 12g, 1.2g corresponds to 1.2/12 = 0.1 moles. Therefore, the number of atoms is 0.1 moles x 6.02 x 10^23 atoms/mol = 6.02 x 10^22 atoms.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>21","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"ACIDS, BASES AND SALTS : ACIDS","question":"Tetraoxosulphate (lV) acid is described as strong acid because it is highly","images":[],"options":{"A":"corrosive","B":"concentrated","C":"reactive","D":"ionized in water"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Tetraoxosulphate (IV) acid, commonly known as sulfuric acid (H2SO4), is considered a strong acid because it ionizes completely in water, producing a high concentration of hydrogen ions (H+). This complete ionization is what characterizes a strong acid.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>22","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"REDOX REACTIONS : OXIDATION AND REDUCTION PROCESS.","question":"The following will decolourize acidified potassium tetraoxomanganate (VII) solution except","images":[],"options":{"A":"sulphur (lV) oxide","B":"but-3-ene","C":"pentane","D":"hydrogen sulphide"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Pentane is a saturated hydrocarbon (alkane) and does not react with potassium tetraoxomanganate (VII) solution, which is a strong oxidizing agent. The other options, such as sulphur (IV) oxide, but-3-ene, hydrogen sulphide, and propyne, can undergo oxidation and thus would decolorize the solution.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>23","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE ATOM : ATOMIC NUMBER/PROTON NUMBER, NUMBER OF NEUTRONS, ISOTOPES, ATOMIC MASS, MASS NUMBER.","question":"Polyatomicity is illustrated by molecules of","images":[],"options":{"A":"sulphur","B":"carbon (IV) oxide","C":"noble gases","D":"liquefied oxygen"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Polyatomicity refers to the presence of multiple atoms in a molecule. Sulphur (S8) is a polyatomic molecule consisting of eight sulfur atoms. The other options either consist of diatomic molecules (like carbon dioxide) or are monoatomic (noble gases).","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>24","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"METALS AND THEIR COMPOUNDS : EXTRACTION OF METALS","question":"Calcium is usually extracted by the electrolysis of its","images":[],"options":{"A":"trioxonitrate (V)","B":"tetraoxosulphate (IV)","C":"oxide","D":"chloride"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Calcium is extracted not from its oxide, but by the electrolysis of molten calcium chloride (CaCl\u2082).    CaO (calcium oxide) has too high a melting point and is not suitable for electrolysis.    In practice, CaCl\u2082 (sometimes mixed with CaF\u2082 to lower melting point) is electrolyzed","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>25","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"STATES OF MATTER : CHANGES OF STATE OF MATTER.","question":"When naphthalene on heating changes from the solid state directly to the gaseous state it undergoes","images":[],"options":{"A":"evaporation","B":"sublimation","C":"decomposition","D":"combustion"},"answer":"B","explanation":"When naphthalene is heated and changes from solid to gas without passing through a liquid state, it undergoes sublimation. This process is characteristic of certain substances that can transition directly from solid to gas.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>26","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"REDOX REACTIONS : ELECTROLYSIS","question":"Which of the following occurs when an aqueous solution of sodium hydroxide is electrolysed using graphite electrodes?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Sodium metal is produced at the anode","B":"Sodium amalgam is formed at the cathode","C":"Oxygen gas is produced at the anode","D":"The grahite anode dissolves"},"answer":"C","explanation":"During the electrolysis of an aqueous sodium hydroxide solution using graphite electrodes, oxygen gas is produced at the anode. The reaction involves the oxidation of hydroxide ions to form oxygen gas and water.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>27","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"STATES OF MATTER : THE GAS LAWS","question":"If the volume of a given mass of gas at 0oC is 27.3cm3, what will be the volume of the gas at 10oC, pressure remaining constant?","images":[],"options":{"A":"2.73cm3","B":"28.3cm3","C":"37.3cm3","D":"273cm3"},"answer":"B","explanation":"To find the volume of a gas at a different temperature while keeping pressure constant, we can use Charles's Law, which states that V1/T1 = V2/T2. Here, V1 = 27.3 cm\u00b3, T1 = 273 K (0\u00b0C), and T2 = 283 K (10\u00b0C). Rearranging gives V2 = V1 * (T2/T1) = 27.3 * (283/273) \u2248 28.3 cm\u00b3. Therefore, the correct option is 28.3 cm\u00b3.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>28","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC BIOCHEMISTRY AND SYNTHETIC POLYMERS : CARBOHYDRATES","question":"Glucose can be obtained from starch by","images":[],"options":{"A":"hydrogenation","B":"dissoiation","C":"hydrolysis","D":"dialysis"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Glucose can be obtained from starch through hydrolysis, which is a chemical process that involves the breakdown of a compound by reaction with water. In this case, starch (a polysaccharide) is hydrolyzed to yield glucose (a monosaccharide). Therefore, the correct option is hydrolysis.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>29","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"STOICHIOMETRY AND CHEMICAL REACTIONS : AMOUNT OF SUBSTANCE.","question":"How many faradays of electricity are required to liberate 9g aluminium? (AI = 27)","images":[],"options":{"A":"0.1","B":"0.3","C":"1.0","D":"2.7"},"answer":"C","explanation":"To determine the number of faradays required to liberate 9g of aluminum, we use the formula: Faradays = (mass of substance / molar mass) * n, where n is the number of electrons transferred per atom. For aluminum, n = 3 (Al^3+). Molar mass of Al = 27 g/mol. Thus, Faradays = (9g / 27g/mol) * 3 = 1.0. Therefore, the correct option is 1.0.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>30","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"CHEMISTRY OF CARBON COMPOUNDS : ALKANES","question":"When water is dropped on calcium carbide, the gaseous product is an","images":[],"options":{"A":"alkane","B":"alkene","C":"alkyne","D":"alkanol"},"answer":"C","explanation":"When water is added to calcium carbide (CaC2), it reacts to produce acetylene gas (C2H2), which is an alkyne. Alkynes are hydrocarbons that contain at least one triple bond between carbon atoms. Therefore, the correct option is alkyne.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>31","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"STOICHIOMETRY AND CHEMICAL REACTIONS : AMOUNT OF SUBSTANCE.","question":"Mg2 + 2HCI(aq) \u2192 MgCI2(g) + H2(g)  From the equation above what mass of hydrogen would be produced if 12.0 g of magnesium reacted completely with dilute hydrochloric acid? (H = 1, Mg = 24)","images":[],"options":{"A":"1.0g","B":"2.0g","C":"6.0g","D":"12.0g"},"answer":"A","explanation":"From the balanced equation, 1 mole of magnesium produces 1 mole of hydrogen. The molar mass of magnesium is 24 g, and the molar mass of hydrogen is 2 g. Therefore, 12 g of magnesium (which is 0.5 moles) will produce 0.5 moles of hydrogen, which is 0.5 * 2 g = 1.0 g of hydrogen. Thus, the correct option is 1.0 g.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>32","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"PERIODIC CHEMISTRY : PERIODIC LAW","question":"The position of an element in the Periodic Table is determined by","images":[],"options":{"A":"its density","B":"its atomic radius","C":"its relative atomic mass","D":"the number of protons in its atom"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The position of an element in the Periodic Table is determined by the number of protons in its atom, which is also known as the atomic number. The atomic number uniquely identifies an element and determines its position in the periodic table.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>33","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"CHEMISTRY OF CARBON COMPOUNDS : ALKANOLS","question":"Which of the following alkanols on oxidation is most likely to yield the compound with formula below?  CH3CHCOOH   |  CH3","images":[],"options":{"A":"Butanol","B":"Propan-2-ol","C":"2-methylbutan-1-ol","D":"2-methylpropan-1-ol"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The compound with the formula CH3CH(COOH)CH3 is 2-propanoic acid (or propanoic acid). The oxidation of propan-2-ol (isopropanol) will yield this compound. The other options do not lead to the formation of this specific carboxylic acid upon oxidation.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>34","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"NON METALS AND THEIR COMPOUNDS : THE NOBLE GASES","question":"Which of the following electronic structures belongs to a noble gas?","images":[],"options":{"A":"1s22s2","B":"1s22s22p4","C":"1s22s22p63s23p6","D":"1s22s22p2"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The electronic structure 1s22s22p63s23p6 corresponds to the noble gas Argon (Ar), which has a complete outer shell of electrons. Noble gases are characterized by having full valence shells, making them stable and unreactive.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>35","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"CHEMICAL KINETICS AND EQUILIBRIUM SYSTEM : RATE OF REACTIONS","question":"In a chemical reaction, the reacting species possess energy of motion known as","images":[],"options":{"A":"potential energy","B":"free energy","C":"bond energy","D":"kinetic energy"},"answer":"D","explanation":"In a chemical reaction, the energy of motion possessed by the reacting species is known as kinetic energy. Kinetic energy is the energy that an object has due to its motion, and in the context of chemical reactions, it relates to the movement of molecules and atoms.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>36","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"CHEMICAL REACTIONS : AMOUNT OF SUBSTANCE","question":"The following compounds will decompose on heating except","images":[],"options":{"A":"NaHCO3","B":"K2CO3","C":"MgCO3","D":"Ca(HCO3)2"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Among the compounds listed, K2CO3 (potassium carbonate) does not decompose upon heating. The other compounds listed, such as NaHCO3 (sodium bicarbonate), MgCO3 (magnesium carbonate), Ca(HCO3)2 (calcium bicarbonate), and ZnCO3 (zinc carbonate), decompose when heated to release gases or form other compounds.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>37","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"ACIDS, BASES AND SALTS : ACID-BASE REACTIONS","question":"Which of the following reactions is accompanied by the first ionization energy of an element X?","images":[],"options":{"A":"X+(aq) \u2192 X2+(aq) + e-","B":"X-(g) \u2192 X(g) + e-","C":"X+(g) \u2192 X2+ + e-","D":"X(g) \u2192 X+(g) + e-"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The reaction X(g) \u2192 X+(g) + e- represents the first ionization energy of an element X. Ionization energy is the energy required to remove an electron from a neutral atom in the gas phase, resulting in a positively charged ion.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>38","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"CHEMISTRY OF CARBON COMPOUNDS : ALKYNES","question":"What is the molar mass of an alkyne with the formula CxH14? (H=1, C=12)","images":[],"options":{"A":"86g","B":"92g","C":"98g","D":"110g"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The formula CxH14 indicates that the alkyne has 14 hydrogen atoms. For an alkyne, the general formula is CnH2n-2. Setting 2n-2 = 14 gives n = 8. Therefore, the molar mass is calculated as (8 * 12) + (14 * 1) = 96 + 14 = 110 g. Thus, the correct answer is 110g.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>39","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"REDOX REACTIONS : OXIDATION AND REDUCTION PROCESS.","question":"What is the role of hydrogen sulphide gas in the reaction represented by the following equation?H2SO4(aq) + 3H2S(g) \u2192 4S(s) + 4H2O(l)","images":[],"options":{"A":"Reducing agent","B":"A bleaching agent","C":"A dehydrating agent","D":"A sulphonating agent"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Hydrogen sulphide (H\u2082S) changes from oxidation state \u20132 in H\u2082S to 0 in elemental sulphur (S). This means it is oxidized.    The substance that is oxidized is the reducing agent.    At the same time, H\u2082SO\u2084 (sulphur in +6) is reduced to water (sulphur leaves as solid S).    \ud83d\udc49 Hence, H\u2082S acts as the reducing agent because it donates electrons and causes H\u2082SO\u2084 to be reduced.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>40","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"CHEMISTRY OF CARBON COMPOUNDS : ALKANOLS","question":"Alkanols have unexpectedly high boiling points relative to their molar masses because of intermolecular","images":[],"options":{"A":"hydrogen bonding","B":"metallic bonding","C":"covalent bonding","D":"ionic bonding"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Alkanols (alcohols) have high boiling points due to hydrogen bonding between their molecules. This type of bonding occurs when a hydrogen atom covalently bonded to a highly electronegative atom (like oxygen) is attracted to another electronegative atom in a different molecule. This strong intermolecular force requires more energy (in the form of heat) to break, resulting in higher boiling points compared to similar-sized molecules that do not exhibit hydrogen bonding.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>41","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"ACIDS, BASES AND SALTS : SALTS","question":"Sodium chloride is used in the following processes except in the","images":[],"options":{"A":"treatment of polluted water","B":"preservation of food","C":"separation of soap from glycerol","D":"manufacture of chlorine"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Sodium chloride (table salt) is commonly used in the treatment of polluted water, preservation of food, and in the manufacture of chlorine and caustic soda. However, it is not used in the separation of soap from glycerol, which typically involves other methods such as centrifugation or filtration.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>42","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"NON METALS AND THEIR COMPOUNDS : HYDROGEN","question":"The gaseous product formed when ammonia is passed over heated copper (ll) oxide is","images":[],"options":{"A":"oxygen","B":"nitrogen","C":"hydrogen","D":"nitrogen (l) oxide"},"answer":"B","explanation":"When ammonia (NH\u2083) is passed over heated copper(II) oxide (CuO), the ammonia is oxidized while CuO is reduced. Ammonia (NH\u2083) acts as the reducing agent because it loses hydrogen and is oxidized.    Copper(II) oxide (CuO) acts as the oxidizing agent because it loses oxygen and is reduced to copper metal.    The final gaseous product is nitrogen (N\u2082), while copper metal and water are also formed.    Thus, the gaseous product is nitrogen, not oxygen or oxides of nitrogen.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>43","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"NON METALS AND THEIR COMPOUNDS : HALOGENS","question":"Which of the following is not a halogen?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Silicon","B":"Fluorine","C":"Astatine","D":"Bromine"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Silicon is not a halogen. Halogens are a group of elements in Group 17 of the periodic table, which includes fluorine, chlorine, bromine, iodine, and astatine. Silicon, on the other hand, is a metalloid found in Group 14 and does not share the chemical properties of halogens.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>44","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"WATER","question":"Which of the following is likely to have the highest degree of hardness?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Carbonated water","B":"Distilled water","C":"Acidified water","D":"Lime water"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Lime water, which is a saturated solution of calcium hydroxide, is known for its hardness due to the presence of dissolved minerals. In contrast, the other options like carbonated water, distilled water, acidified water, and rainwater generally have lower hardness levels.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>45","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"CHEMISTRY OF CARBON COMPOUNDS : ALKANOLS~~CHEMISTRY OF CARBON COMPOUNDS : ALKANOIC ACIDS~~CHEMISTRY OF CARBON COMPOUNDS : ALKANOATES AS DRIVATIVES OF ALKANOIC ACIDS","question":"Study the reaction represented by the equation: Alkanol + Alkanoic acid + conc. H2SO4 \u2192  Alkanoate + water.  The type of process involved in the reverse reaction is","images":[],"options":{"A":"Neutralization","B":"dehydration","C":"hydrolysis","D":"decomposition"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The reverse reaction of the given equation involves the hydrolysis of the alkanoate to regenerate the alkanol and alkanoic acid. Hydrolysis is a chemical process that involves the reaction of a compound with water, leading to the breakdown of that compound.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>46","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"CHEMICAL BONDS : IONIC COMPOUNDS","question":"Destructive distillation of coal means","images":[],"options":{"A":"heating coal in plentiful supply of air","B":"burning coal in air to produce water and carbon (IV) oxide","C":"heating coal in the absence of air","D":"heating coal in limited supply of air"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Destructive distillation of coal refers to heating coal in the absence of air. This process breaks down the coal into various products, including coal gas, coal tar, and coke, without combustion occurring.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>47","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"ACIDS, BASES AND SALTS : ACIDS","question":"When magnesium ribbon burns in air, the products are","images":[],"options":{"A":"magnesium nitride and magnesium oxide","B":"magnesium nitride and carbon (ll) oxide","C":"magnesium oxide and steam","D":"magnesium nitride and soot"},"answer":"A","explanation":"When magnesium ribbon burns in air, it reacts with oxygen to form magnesium oxide (MgO). The presence of nitrogen in the air can lead to the formation of magnesium nitride (Mg3N2) under certain conditions, but the primary product is magnesium oxide.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>48","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"CHEMICAL BONDS : IONIC COMPOUNDS","question":"The following compounds contain the same type of bonds except","images":[],"options":{"A":"sodium chloride","B":"hydrogen chloride","C":"magnesium chloride","D":"potassium chloride"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Most of the compounds listed \u2014 sodium chloride (NaCl), magnesium chloride (MgCl\u2082), potassium chloride (KCl), and lithium chloride (LiCl) \u2014 are ionic compounds. They are formed by the transfer of electrons from the metal atom to chlorine, resulting in strong electrostatic forces between oppositely charged ions.    However, hydrogen chloride (HCl) is different. In its gaseous state, HCl is a covalent compound because the hydrogen and chlorine atoms share electrons rather than transferring them. (Only when dissolved in water does it ionize to form H\u207a and Cl\u207b ions, behaving like an acid.)    Therefore, the compound that does not contain the same type of ionic bond as the others is hydrogen chloride (HCl).","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>49","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"REDOX REACTIONS : ELECTROCHEMICAL CELLS","question":"The part labelled X is the","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"options":{"A":"galvanometer","B":"voltmeter","C":"ammeter","D":"salt bridge"},"answer":"D","explanation":"A salt bridge is a tube or strip containing an inert electrolyte in a gel or porous medium, which connects the two half-cells of an electrochemical cell.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Chemistry>1994>50","subject":"Chemistry","year":"1994","type":"Objective","topic":"REDOX REACTIONS : OXIDATION AND REDUCTION PROCESS.","question":"The reaction at the zinc anode is","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"options":{"A":"addition","B":"hydrolysis","C":"oxidation","D":"hydration"},"answer":"C","explanation":"In an electrochemical cell:    Anode \u2192 Oxidation (loss of electrons)    Cathode \u2192 Reduction (gain of electrons)    So, in the Daniell cell:    At the zinc anode: Zn \u2192 Zn\u00b2\u207a + 2e\u207b (oxidation)    At the copper cathode: Cu\u00b2\u207a + 2e\u207b \u2192 Cu (reduction)  Addition   Addition means combining two or more molecules/atoms to form one product (e.g.,   At the anode, zinc is not combining with anything. Instead, it is losing electrons.  So this is not addition.  Hydrolysis   Hydrolysis means decomposition of a compound by reaction with water (e.g., ester hydrolysis).  The zinc electrode is not reacting with water. It simply dissolves as ions by losing electrons.  So, not hydrolysis.  Oxidation  (Correct)    At the anode, electrons are always lost.    Zinc loses electrons:  This is the definition of oxidation.  Hydration   Hydration means adding water molecules to a compound (e.g., CuSO\u2084\u00b75H\u2082O is hydrated copper sulfate).  Zinc is not combining with water molecules; it is just losing electrons.  So, not hydration.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"}];